453":"1453","about 1326":"about 1326","Abt 1352":"about 1352","1328":"1328","Of, Harpole, Northampton, England":"Harpole, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","Of,Harpole,Northampton,England":"Harpole, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","Harpole, Northamptonshire, England":"Harpole, Northamptonshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Tame","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name primarily from Thame in Oxfordshire, or the river Thame which flows through it, but perhaps occasionally from one or more of the three English rivers named Tame, in Staffordshire/Warwickshire, Yorkshire, and Yorkshire/Lancashire. The river names are probably all related to the Indo-European root <i>tā-</i>, <i>tə-</i> ‘melt, flow’. Thame in Oxfordshire takes its name from the river Thame."],"variants":[{"name":"Thames","meanings":["English (London and Kent):","topographic name from the river Thames in southeastern England. The river name is related to the Indo-European root <i>tā-</i>, <i>tə-</i> ‘melt, flow’.","variant of   Tame  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":2,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace betwee